# <%= current_page.data.title %>

## Overview

Core shared services production account hosts shared services account resources. 

| Resource | Description |
|----------------- |------------------------------------------------
| S3 | Stores essential logging data such as EC2 Image builder logs
| KMS | Contains customer-managed CMK (with associated alias and key policy) used for encryption of EBS volumes and snapshots backing AMIs generated from image builder
| ECR| Hosts docker container images for the deployment and management of containerized applications
| IAM | Contains roles for various services, such as VPC Flow Logs, Image Builder, and cross-account access.
| Microsoft Active Directory Controllers | Provide centralised identity and access management for customer environments
| VPC | Contains live_data and non_live_data VPCs
| Instance Scheduler Lambda | Manage start/stop schedules for non-critical instances, optimizing resource usage and cost-efficiency.


## AWS Account Setup

In the event that you need to receate this account, Use AWS Organizations to create a new account named "core-shared-services". 
Ensure the account is part of the Modernisation Platform Core Organisational Unit (OU) and apply relevant Service Control Policies (SCPs) to the account.

## Recreation of resources 

This can be achieved by triggering core-shared-services deployment workflow run, which can be (found here)[https://github.com/ministryofjustice/modernisation-platform/actions/runs/10073457872/workflow]
Alternatively, this can be done locally: 
- Navigate to the 'modernisation-platfom repo' and change to the core-shared-services directory 
- Initialise terraform and use the MP credentials
- Run terraform plan in production workspace
- Examine the output to ensure that all changes are as expected and no unintended changes are proposed.
- Using admin credentials, execute terraform apply
- Log into the account in the console and check that resources have been correctly provisioned and configured.

If discrepancies are found, investigate the Terraform state and apply logs to identify potential issues.
Make necessary adjustments and reapply Terraform configurations as needed.


More details can be found in our [disaster recovery process] (https://user-guide.modernisation-platform.service.justice.gov.uk/runbooks/dr-process.html))

## IAM Roles and Policies

The following outlines some of the key IAM configurations in the core-shared services production account:

| Role | Role Name | Purpose | Role Policy
|----------------- |------------------------------------------------
VPC Flow Logs IAM Role	| AWSVPCFlowLog | Allows VPC Flow Logs to publish logs to CloudWatch | Grants necessary permissions for log actions such as creating log groups and putting log events.
Image Builder IAM Role |	Image-builder |	Allows EC2 Image Builder to use specified policies for creating and managing AMIs | Includes permissions for EC2 instance profile and SSM managed policies.
Instance Scheduler Lambda IAM Role | InstanceSchedulerAccess | Allows the Lambda function to start and stop EC2 instances and publish logs to CloudWatch | Grants permissions for log actions and EC2 instance management.
Cross-Account Access Roles | AWS-SSM-AutomationAdministrationRole | Allows cross-account access for SSM automation and administration tasks | Includes permissions for SSM actions and trust relationships.
OIDC Configuration for Core-Shared Services| 	| Allows GitHub Actions to interact with AWS resources securely | Grants permissions for actions such as updating Lambda code and decrypting KMS keys.

